WEBVTT

00:01.736 --> 00:04.236
A space experiment goes
horribly wrong.

00:04.238 --> 00:06.071
LUSK:
He was stuck in this chamber,

00:06.073 --> 00:09.641
and there was no way
for him to save himself.

00:09.643 --> 00:13.245
A secret soldier determined
to serve her country.

00:13.247 --> 00:16.482
She was taking a risk.
There's no question about it.

00:16.484 --> 00:17.816
♪♪

00:17.818 --> 00:22.354
And a naval code breaker
races to stop a deadly attack.

00:22.356 --> 00:25.624
You're talking about a critical,
critical situation.

00:25.626 --> 00:27.860
♪♪

00:27.862 --> 00:30.396
These are
the "Mysteries at the Museum."

00:30.398 --> 00:35.267
♪♪

00:35.269 --> 00:38.604
The Big Apple has more
skyscrapers than any other city

00:38.606 --> 00:40.706
in the United States,

00:40.708 --> 00:44.843
and the tallest of them
is One World Trade Center.

00:44.845 --> 00:49.715
This gleaming edifice reaches
a height of 1,776 feet,

00:49.717 --> 00:51.250
a symbolic nod to the year

00:51.252 --> 00:54.052
the Declaration of Independence
was signed.

00:55.423 --> 00:58.056
And at its base
are two reflecting pools

00:58.058 --> 01:00.058
built in the footprints
of the Twin Towers

01:00.060 --> 01:01.693
that fell in 2001,

01:01.695 --> 01:04.530
to remember the lives lost
on that fateful day.

01:04.532 --> 01:05.864
These are a part of

01:05.866 --> 01:09.234
the National September 11th
Memorial & Museum.

01:10.771 --> 01:14.106
Included in the collection are
remnants of the antenna

01:14.108 --> 01:16.842
that once adorned
the North Tower,

01:16.844 --> 01:19.178
a steel beam known as
the last column

01:19.180 --> 01:21.146
that rescue workers
covered with tributes

01:21.148 --> 01:23.849
in the aftermath of the attacks,

01:23.851 --> 01:25.317
and a mangled fire truck

01:25.319 --> 01:28.353
once driven by the crew
of Ladder Company 3,

01:28.355 --> 01:29.822
who were among
the first responders

01:29.824 --> 01:32.090
to the scene that fateful day.

01:34.228 --> 01:36.495
But alongside these
heart-wrenching reminders

01:36.497 --> 01:39.231
of a terrible tragedy
is something

01:39.233 --> 01:42.034
that gave the nation
a new resolve.

01:42.036 --> 01:45.404
RAMIREZ: The artifact is
3 feet high by 5 feet wide.

01:45.406 --> 01:47.973
It's made of lightweight fabric.

01:47.975 --> 01:52.311
It has four segments
of nylon braided roping.

01:52.313 --> 01:55.647
Some of those pieces have been
spliced together

01:55.649 --> 01:57.483
with black electrical tape.

01:57.485 --> 02:01.487
It is an artifact that
every American would recognize.

02:01.489 --> 02:04.923
♪♪

02:04.925 --> 02:07.192
WILDMAN: This flag was
at the center of a mystery

02:07.194 --> 02:10.562
that unfurled in
the darkest of times.

02:10.564 --> 02:13.465
RAMIREZ: This is a story about
a destructive day,

02:13.467 --> 02:16.001
a symbol of hope
that sprung out of it,

02:16.003 --> 02:19.104
and a very confusing mix-up.

02:19.106 --> 02:23.976
♪♪

02:23.978 --> 02:26.812
WILDMAN:
It's September 11th, 2001.

02:26.814 --> 02:29.948
Two planes have just been flown
into the World Trade Center,

02:29.950 --> 02:32.351
marking the single deadliest
terrorist attack

02:32.353 --> 02:35.454
on American soil
in the nation's history.

02:35.456 --> 02:40.592
Nearly 3,000 innocent civilians
have lost their lives.

02:40.594 --> 02:43.795
Later that day, a group
of determined firefighters

02:43.797 --> 02:47.165
stand atop a mountain of rubble
from the fallen towers.

02:47.167 --> 02:50.102
In their hands is
a battered American flag,

02:50.104 --> 02:52.237
held together
with electrical tape.

02:52.239 --> 02:54.740
The raising of the flag
was probably

02:54.742 --> 02:59.344
the most purposeful action
of that horrible day.

02:59.346 --> 03:02.347
♪♪

03:02.349 --> 03:03.615
WILDMAN:
In the days that follow,

03:03.617 --> 03:05.551
a photograph of this
solemn moment,

03:05.553 --> 03:08.287
taken by photojournalist
Thomas E. Franklin,

03:08.289 --> 03:09.855
is printed in newspapers

03:09.857 --> 03:13.392
and broadcast on TV stations
around the world,

03:13.394 --> 03:15.193
an echo of the famous picture

03:15.195 --> 03:17.129
of the Marines hoisting
the American flag

03:17.131 --> 03:20.299
over the island of Iwo Jima
during World War II.

03:20.301 --> 03:24.536
The photograph goes on to become
a finalist for a Pulitzer Prize.

03:24.538 --> 03:28.240
RAMIREZ: The image was a symbol
of the resolve,

03:28.242 --> 03:30.275
the resourcefulness,

03:30.277 --> 03:32.144
the stoic grit

03:32.146 --> 03:36.014
of those who were going
to unravel this horrible mess

03:36.016 --> 03:40.485
and allow the nation
to take the next steps forward.

03:40.487 --> 03:42.354
WILDMAN: But as the photograph
takes its place

03:42.356 --> 03:44.156
in the canon of history,

03:44.158 --> 03:46.925
some begin to wonder
about the flag itself.

03:46.927 --> 03:50.329
Where did the flag come from,
and where is it now?

03:50.331 --> 03:52.965
And so begins one of
the strangest chapters

03:52.967 --> 03:57.002
in the tragic story of 9/11.

03:57.004 --> 04:00.339
One woman who thinks she knows
where the 9/11 flag came from

04:00.341 --> 04:03.408
is a New Yorker
named Shirley Dreifus.

04:03.410 --> 04:05.744
Shirley Dreifus and her husband

04:05.746 --> 04:08.814
were the owners of
a luxury yacht business.

04:08.816 --> 04:13.051
Their two boats were moored
in the North Cove Marina

04:13.053 --> 04:14.886
near the World Trade Center.

04:17.458 --> 04:19.524
WILDMAN:
Shortly after September 11th,

04:19.526 --> 04:23.528
Dreifus was told that one of her
boats was missing its ensign,

04:23.530 --> 04:26.064
a 3-by-5-foot
star-spangled banner,

04:26.066 --> 04:29.635
the exact same size as the one
in the famous photo.

04:29.637 --> 04:31.069
Not only that,

04:31.071 --> 04:32.971
but the firefighters
in the photograph

04:32.973 --> 04:36.408
also state that they took
the flag from a nearby yacht.

04:36.410 --> 04:39.611
It seems that Dreifus
is indeed the flag's owner.

04:39.613 --> 04:41.880
Shirley Dreifus began
to recognize

04:41.882 --> 04:45.984
this was potentially
the icon of the century.

04:48.188 --> 04:51.323
WILDMAN: In the months that
follow, the flag is included

04:51.325 --> 04:53.392
in a touring collection
of artifacts

04:53.394 --> 04:54.926
and appears at benefit concerts

04:54.928 --> 04:58.096
and fund-raising events
around the world.

04:58.098 --> 05:00.365
But when Dreifus decides
to hold a fund-raiser

05:00.367 --> 05:02.467
to benefit local firefighters

05:02.469 --> 05:04.536
and asks city officials
for permission

05:04.538 --> 05:07.205
to borrow back her famous flag
for the event,

05:07.207 --> 05:09.908
she gets a shocking surprise.

05:09.910 --> 05:12.477
The flag the city sends her
is much bigger

05:12.479 --> 05:14.613
than the one she had
on her yacht.

05:14.615 --> 05:16.682
When they opened it up,

05:16.684 --> 05:20.285
they realized it was about
2 feet too big.

05:20.287 --> 05:25.090
She knew the size of their flag,
and she knew this was not it.

05:25.092 --> 05:26.425
WILDMAN: Not only that,

05:26.427 --> 05:28.660
but the distinctive black
electrical tape

05:28.662 --> 05:30.829
that's so noticeable
in the original photograph

05:30.831 --> 05:32.497
is nowhere to be found.

05:32.499 --> 05:35.867
It seems as if
it's the wrong flag.

05:35.869 --> 05:38.537
In the chaos of the events
after 9/11,

05:38.539 --> 05:43.141
the actual flag in the iconic
photo somehow disappeared.

05:43.143 --> 05:47.145
For over a decade, there's
no sign of the 9/11 flag.

05:47.147 --> 05:49.981
What happened to it
was a continuing mystery.

05:49.983 --> 05:55.153
♪♪

05:55.155 --> 05:59.091
WILDMAN: In 2014, in the small
town of Everett, Washington,

05:59.093 --> 06:01.259
a history buff
named Brian Browne

06:01.261 --> 06:03.428
is watching television
when he sees a report

06:03.430 --> 06:06.531
about Dreifus
and the missing 9/11 flag.

06:06.533 --> 06:08.433
The story strikes a chord.

06:10.637 --> 06:11.803
Eight years earlier,

06:11.805 --> 06:14.005
he had purchased a flag
for his collection

06:14.007 --> 06:16.908
that he was told had come
from Ground Zero.

06:16.910 --> 06:20.078
RAMIREZ: The World Trade Center
site was full of American flags.

06:20.080 --> 06:21.713
There were
government offices there.

06:21.715 --> 06:23.582
The Port Authority of New York
and New Jersey

06:23.584 --> 06:25.484
routinely flew flags,

06:25.486 --> 06:29.221
so for a flag to have turned up
with the Ground Zero provenance

06:29.223 --> 06:32.324
was not in any way that unusual.

06:32.326 --> 06:34.092
WILDMAN: But when Browne
compares his flag

06:34.094 --> 06:35.694
to the one in the famous photo,

06:35.696 --> 06:38.130
he notices something
extraordinary.

06:38.132 --> 06:40.966
His flag has a strip
of black electrical tape

06:40.968 --> 06:43.502
in the same spot as the picture.

06:43.504 --> 06:45.537
Browne is convinced
that his flag

06:45.539 --> 06:48.507
and the flag in the photograph
are one and the same.

06:48.509 --> 06:52.944
Brian Browne turned the flag
into the authorities in Everett.

06:52.946 --> 06:55.747
His goal was to make sure
that the people of New York

06:55.749 --> 06:59.017
and the rightful owners
would have the restitution

06:59.019 --> 07:01.586
of this incredible
cultural property.

07:01.588 --> 07:04.723
♪♪

07:04.725 --> 07:07.392
WILDMAN: Officials carefully
examine Browne's flag

07:07.394 --> 07:09.861
and confirm that it is indeed
the same ensign

07:09.863 --> 07:11.830
that was taken
from Shirley Dreifus' boat

07:11.832 --> 07:13.231
by the firefighters

07:13.233 --> 07:15.634
and raised over the ruins
of the Towers

07:15.636 --> 07:17.135
in the famous photograph.

07:17.137 --> 07:19.805
It's believed that
in the days after 9/11,

07:19.807 --> 07:22.841
this flag had been given
to the widow of a firefighter,

07:22.843 --> 07:24.342
who later sold it,

07:24.344 --> 07:28.680
and it eventually ended up in
the possession of Brian Browne.

07:28.682 --> 07:32.184
In 2016, the flag
is given back to Dreifus,

07:32.186 --> 07:35.020
who promptly donates it
to the city for posterity.

07:35.022 --> 07:36.354
She cried.

07:36.356 --> 07:41.326
I mean, this was her dream
finally come true.

07:41.328 --> 07:42.961
Out of a nightmare of a day,

07:42.963 --> 07:47.265
this very positive ending
was happening.

07:47.267 --> 07:49.034
She was so thrilled.

07:49.036 --> 07:52.037
♪♪

07:52.039 --> 07:54.573
WILDMAN: Today, the flag can
be seen on display

07:54.575 --> 07:57.309
at the National September 11th
Memorial & Museum

07:57.311 --> 07:59.110
in New York City.

07:59.112 --> 08:02.447
It's a resounding symbol of hope
that rose from the ruins

08:02.449 --> 08:05.016
in one of America's
darkest hours.

08:05.018 --> 08:08.587
♪♪

08:08.589 --> 08:10.689
Huntsville, Alabama,
was once home

08:10.691 --> 08:13.792
to a record-breaking Jersey cow
named Lily Flagg.

08:13.794 --> 08:18.496
In 1892, this prodigious bovine
produced enough milk

08:18.498 --> 08:21.299
to make more than
1,000 pounds of butter

08:21.301 --> 08:24.636
and even appeared at
the Chicago World's Fair.

08:24.638 --> 08:28.406
But today, the city has a very
different claim to fame --

08:28.408 --> 08:31.142
space exploration.

08:31.144 --> 08:33.044
Nowhere is that more evident

08:33.046 --> 08:35.380
than the U.S. Space
& Rocket Center.

08:37.651 --> 08:41.953
On display are a set
of security badges worn by VIPs

08:41.955 --> 08:46.024
at a series of iconic
NASA mission launches,

08:46.026 --> 08:50.962
the command module from the 1972
Apollo 16 trip to the moon,

08:50.964 --> 08:52.898
and a mobile quarantine facility

08:52.900 --> 08:55.834
for use by astronauts
on their return to Earth.

08:55.836 --> 08:58.203
♪♪

08:58.205 --> 09:00.472
But there's one item here
without which

09:00.474 --> 09:02.941
no trip to space can
be complete.

09:02.943 --> 09:05.911
LUSK: The artifact has a red
and blue nozzle.

09:05.913 --> 09:08.213
It is slender and ribbed.

09:08.215 --> 09:11.182
It has two round tubes that are
connected to each other.

09:11.184 --> 09:15.487
♪♪

09:15.489 --> 09:18.156
WILDMAN: For any space traveler,
this simple hose

09:18.158 --> 09:20.592
is the difference between
life and death.

09:20.594 --> 09:23.762
This is a story about
quick thinking under pressure.

09:23.764 --> 09:31.369
♪♪

09:31.371 --> 09:34.839
WILDMAN: It's the 1960s
in Houston, Texas.

09:34.841 --> 09:37.242
The United States
is locked in a space race

09:37.244 --> 09:38.877
with the Soviet Union.

09:38.879 --> 09:40.211
The ultimate goal --

09:40.213 --> 09:43.448
to be the first nation
to put a man on the moon.

09:43.450 --> 09:47.352
The U.S. wants to do anything
they can to get a leg up.

09:47.354 --> 09:51.723
They are throwing tons of
resources into the NASA program,

09:51.725 --> 09:55.193
but in the process,
everything's happening so fast.

09:55.195 --> 09:57.595
There's a high risk potential.

09:57.597 --> 10:00.832
Something could go wrong.

10:00.834 --> 10:02.467
WILDMAN:
To ensure that the astronauts

10:02.469 --> 10:05.337
are safe for their trip
to the lunar surface,

10:05.339 --> 10:08.974
every piece of equipment must be
thoroughly tested on Earth.

10:08.976 --> 10:10.976
There's a lot of safety risks.

10:10.978 --> 10:13.345
It's one thing to be
in a spaceship,

10:13.347 --> 10:16.982
but it's a whole 'nother thing
to take on this new environment

10:16.984 --> 10:19.384
that nobody has ever
been to before.

10:21.655 --> 10:24.422
WILDMAN:
On December 14, 1966,

10:24.424 --> 10:26.157
the team at NASA is testing

10:26.159 --> 10:29.327
one of the most important
pieces of kit --

10:29.329 --> 10:30.428
the space suits.

10:30.430 --> 10:32.030
The suits must be
flexible enough

10:32.032 --> 10:33.999
to allow for a range
of movement,

10:34.001 --> 10:38.536
but also sufficiently strong
to maintain protective pressure.

10:38.538 --> 10:41.406
The tiniest leak in the garment
could prove fatal

10:41.408 --> 10:42.974
to an astronaut.

10:42.976 --> 10:45.176
LUSK: Liquid turns to gas
on the moon,

10:45.178 --> 10:49.781
so because our bodies are made
of 70% liquid,

10:49.783 --> 10:51.816
this was a huge risk.

10:51.818 --> 10:53.785
WILDMAN: So the scientists
at NASA create

10:53.787 --> 10:56.721
a triple-sealed
depressurized chamber

10:56.723 --> 10:58.923
that mimics the atmosphere
of the moon.

10:58.925 --> 11:02.027
The plan is to send
a test subject into the chamber

11:02.029 --> 11:03.695
and simulate walking.

11:03.697 --> 11:06.231
Tasked with the job of
wearing the suit

11:06.233 --> 11:10.502
is NASA technician Jim LeBlanc.

11:10.504 --> 11:12.937
LUSK: LeBlanc was probably
a little nervous

11:12.939 --> 11:14.406
about all these tests,

11:14.408 --> 11:17.776
and he knew that he was just
gonna have to take the risk,

11:17.778 --> 11:20.879
because it was worth it
if it meant getting to the moon.

11:20.881 --> 11:23.081
♪♪

11:23.083 --> 11:24.949
WILDMAN:
When the team is all set,

11:24.951 --> 11:27.352
LeBlanc dons the prototype suit.

11:27.354 --> 11:30.088
LUSK: The pressurized space suit
had a hose

11:30.090 --> 11:31.790
that connected to a system

11:31.792 --> 11:35.593
that would regulate
the pressure inside of the suit.

11:35.595 --> 11:38.363
WILDMAN: The hose,
like the one on display at

11:38.365 --> 11:41.466
the U.S. Space & Rocket Center
in Huntsville, Alabama,

11:41.468 --> 11:45.036
maintains a supply of
breathable air within the suit.

11:45.038 --> 11:47.205
As LeBlanc enters
the vacuum chamber,

11:47.207 --> 11:51.009
the three sets of doors
slowly seal shut behind him.

11:51.011 --> 11:53.278
Then, the process of gradually

11:53.280 --> 11:55.880
depressurizing the chamber
begins.

11:57.284 --> 12:00.452
But as the air slowly drains
out of the room,

12:00.454 --> 12:02.720
LeBlanc feels an odd sensation.

12:02.722 --> 12:05.757
LUSK:
His saliva started to bubble

12:05.759 --> 12:09.527
as if it was turning into gas.

12:09.529 --> 12:12.363
Then he notices something
truly terrifying.

12:12.365 --> 12:14.632
The hose is disconnected,

12:14.634 --> 12:17.735
and his suit is
rapidly losing pressure.

12:17.737 --> 12:20.972
LUSK: LeBlanc feared
for his life,

12:20.974 --> 12:23.041
and there was nothing
he could do.

12:23.043 --> 12:25.877
WILDMAN: The trapped technician
begins to flail.

12:25.879 --> 12:29.481
After 15 seconds,
LeBlanc lost consciousness.

12:31.818 --> 12:33.318
WILDMAN: In the control room,

12:33.320 --> 12:36.254
the NASA engineers are faced
with a terrible dilemma --

12:36.256 --> 12:39.958
let LeBlanc die or risk their
own lives to enter the chamber

12:39.960 --> 12:42.293
without proper repressurization.

12:42.295 --> 12:44.429
You couldn't just go in
and help that person

12:44.431 --> 12:48.066
because you would be exposed
to the environment of the moon.

12:48.068 --> 12:49.868
WILDMAN: But if they flood
the room with air,

12:49.870 --> 12:53.538
the sudden change in pressure
could also kill the tester.

12:53.540 --> 12:55.907
NASA had seconds to save
LeBlanc.

12:55.909 --> 12:58.276
What were the odds
he would make it out alive?

12:58.278 --> 12:59.744
♪♪

12:59.746 --> 13:01.179
MAN:
Repressurize the chamber!

13:03.116 --> 13:04.783
♪♪

13:04.785 --> 13:07.452
It's December 14, 1966,

13:07.454 --> 13:09.654
in Houston, Texas.

13:09.656 --> 13:12.457
NASA technician Jim LeBlanc
is testing out

13:12.459 --> 13:14.426
a prototype space suit

13:14.428 --> 13:16.428
when something
goes terribly wrong.

13:16.430 --> 13:19.364
The hose that keeps
the space suit supplied with air

13:19.366 --> 13:21.699
has become disconnected.

13:21.701 --> 13:25.069
Within moments,
LeBlanc loses consciousness.

13:25.071 --> 13:27.605
So how will
he make it out alive?

13:27.607 --> 13:28.973
♪♪

13:28.975 --> 13:31.042
A NASA engineer named Cliff Hess

13:31.044 --> 13:33.278
must make a fateful decision.

13:33.280 --> 13:36.247
With LeBlanc's life on the line,
Hess has no choice

13:36.249 --> 13:39.083
but to rapidly repressurize
the chamber.

13:41.288 --> 13:43.087
This was a risky move.

13:43.089 --> 13:45.490
Repressurizing this chamber
so quickly

13:45.492 --> 13:48.259
could cause serious
brain damage for LeBlanc,

13:48.261 --> 13:50.462
but Hess had no option.

13:50.464 --> 13:52.664
This was the only way
to save LeBlanc.

13:55.702 --> 13:58.036
WILDMAN: The chamber is suddenly
flooded with air,

13:58.038 --> 14:00.705
and soon after,
the room is safe to enter.

14:09.316 --> 14:11.983
LUSK: Luckily for Hess
and for LeBlanc,

14:11.985 --> 14:15.086
LeBlanc came to
and he was perfectly fine.

14:15.088 --> 14:17.956
WILDMAN: Hess' decisive actions
saved LeBlanc,

14:17.958 --> 14:20.925
who recovers with nothing
worse than an earache.

14:20.927 --> 14:24.796
If Hess had hesitated, it could
have meant LeBlanc's life.

14:24.798 --> 14:26.998
The fact that he acted
so quickly,

14:27.000 --> 14:29.267
that was what saved him.

14:29.269 --> 14:31.102
WILDMAN:
Thanks to tests like these,

14:31.104 --> 14:34.138
3 years later,
on July 20, 1969,

14:34.140 --> 14:37.442
the United States launches
their first lunar mission,

14:37.444 --> 14:39.043
beating the Soviet Union.

14:39.045 --> 14:41.646
We would not have been able
to have sent a man to the moon

14:41.648 --> 14:43.882
without this testing.

14:43.884 --> 14:48.486
♪♪

14:48.488 --> 14:49.821
WILDMAN: Today, this hose,

14:49.823 --> 14:52.357
used during the testing
for the Apollo missions,

14:52.359 --> 14:55.326
is in the collection of
the U.S. Space & Rocket Center

14:55.328 --> 14:57.128
in Huntsville, Alabama.

14:57.130 --> 15:00.565
It serves as a reminder
of a high-pressure situation

15:00.567 --> 15:03.001
and the engineer
who saved the day.

15:03.003 --> 15:07.105
♪♪

15:07.107 --> 15:10.008
Founded in 1729,
Baltimore, Maryland,

15:10.010 --> 15:13.745
is a bustling port city
located on the Chesapeake Bay,

15:13.747 --> 15:16.648
so it's no surprise the area's
most famous cuisine,

15:16.650 --> 15:19.017
the crab cake,
comes from these waters,

15:19.019 --> 15:23.288
which are home to more than
550 million blue crabs.

15:23.290 --> 15:25.924
The first recipe
dates back to 1939

15:25.926 --> 15:29.193
and was originally called
the Baltimore crab cake.

15:29.195 --> 15:32.697
But 20 miles inland, in the town
of Annapolis Junction,

15:32.699 --> 15:35.033
travelers can experience
a different side

15:35.035 --> 15:36.434
of the region's culture.

15:36.436 --> 15:39.304
This is
the National Cryptologic Museum.

15:41.641 --> 15:45.944
It's dedicated to the art
of code making and breaking.

15:45.946 --> 15:49.247
Items on display include
the first known book

15:49.249 --> 15:52.850
on the topic,
published in 1518,

15:52.852 --> 15:55.486
an encryption device
invented by Thomas Jefferson

15:55.488 --> 15:57.989
in the 1700s,

15:57.991 --> 15:59.724
and a part from Colossus,

15:59.726 --> 16:02.427
the first large-scale
electronic computer,

16:02.429 --> 16:04.562
developed during World War II.

16:04.564 --> 16:07.365
♪♪

16:07.367 --> 16:10.268
But one item here stands apart.

16:10.270 --> 16:13.638
WEADON: The artifact is black
and made of shiny metal.

16:13.640 --> 16:16.307
It has buttons
that one can press.

16:16.309 --> 16:19.978
It is a device that was used
in classified operations.

16:19.980 --> 16:22.246
Very few of these exist
in the world.

16:22.248 --> 16:25.450
♪♪

16:25.452 --> 16:28.953
WILDMAN: This mysterious machine
recalls a critical mission

16:28.955 --> 16:32.223
that helped America
turn the tide in World War II.

16:32.225 --> 16:34.225
WEADON: This is a story of how
a brilliant man

16:34.227 --> 16:36.361
was able to outsmart the enemy.

16:36.363 --> 16:44.068
♪♪

16:44.070 --> 16:47.071
WILDMAN:
It's December 1941.

16:47.073 --> 16:49.674
Following the surprise attack
on Pearl Harbor,

16:49.676 --> 16:51.643
the United States is reeling.

16:51.645 --> 16:53.344
The preemptive strike has killed

16:53.346 --> 16:55.747
more than 2,000
American soldiers

16:55.749 --> 16:58.449
and decimated the Pacific fleet,

16:58.451 --> 17:03.121
destroying some 300 airplanes
and 20 naval vessels.

17:03.123 --> 17:05.990
The attack on Pearl Harbor was
completely unexpected.

17:05.992 --> 17:09.527
It was a complete surprise.

17:09.529 --> 17:10.862
WILDMAN: One man who takes

17:10.864 --> 17:13.698
the terrible turn of events
particularly hard

17:13.700 --> 17:18.369
is 41-year-old cryptologist and
naval officer Joseph Rochefort.

17:18.371 --> 17:20.538
Rochefort was
the complete package.

17:20.540 --> 17:22.640
He was fluent in Japanese.

17:22.642 --> 17:24.642
He had a good understanding

17:24.644 --> 17:27.111
of how the Navy cryptologic
system worked.

17:27.113 --> 17:29.280
♪♪

17:29.282 --> 17:30.782
WILDMAN:
Rochefort is the head

17:30.784 --> 17:34.252
of the American code-breaking
group known as Station HYPO.

17:34.254 --> 17:37.488
WEADON: Station HYPO was part of
the United States Navy efforts

17:37.490 --> 17:39.657
to track Japanese movements

17:39.659 --> 17:42.794
and collect information
out in the Pacific.

17:42.796 --> 17:45.630
WILDMAN: Rochefort
feels a gnawing sense of guilt.

17:45.632 --> 17:48.733
It was his job to detect
the signs that such an attack

17:48.735 --> 17:50.868
was coming, and he failed.

17:50.870 --> 17:52.770
WEADON: There is no one who
feels more ashamed

17:52.772 --> 17:54.772
of what happened
than Joseph Rochefort.

17:54.774 --> 17:58.009
♪♪

17:58.011 --> 18:00.445
WILDMAN: But he's determined
to make amends.

18:00.447 --> 18:02.447
In the aftermath of
Pearl Harbor,

18:02.449 --> 18:05.616
he vows that he will crack
the Japanese Naval codes

18:05.618 --> 18:08.186
and prevent any future attacks.

18:08.188 --> 18:10.388
The task is a daunting one.

18:10.390 --> 18:14.158
For 5 months, Rochefort
and his team pore over reams

18:14.160 --> 18:16.694
of encoded
Japanese communications,

18:16.696 --> 18:19.197
and using machines
just like the one on display at

18:19.199 --> 18:22.166
the National Cryptologic Museum
in Maryland,

18:22.168 --> 18:26.537
they try to crack the codes,
but their efforts are in vain.

18:26.539 --> 18:28.806
As soon as they make
the slightest headway,

18:28.808 --> 18:31.209
the Japanese change the codes.

18:31.211 --> 18:32.777
WEADON: Just when you start
to get close,

18:32.779 --> 18:35.279
just when you start to make
some progress,

18:35.281 --> 18:37.915
boom, it's back
to the drawing board.

18:40.787 --> 18:43.387
WILDMAN: Then, in May of 1942,

18:43.389 --> 18:45.256
Rochefort has a breakthrough.

18:45.258 --> 18:47.625
He thinks he's decrypted
part of a message

18:47.627 --> 18:50.027
that says that the next target
will be an island

18:50.029 --> 18:53.631
that harbors some kind
of U.S. military air base.

18:53.633 --> 18:57.034
There are two possible locations
that seem to fit the bill.

18:59.172 --> 19:00.972
The first is Midway Island,

19:00.974 --> 19:03.407
an American
air and submarine base

19:03.409 --> 19:06.477
1,300 miles northwest of Hawaii.

19:06.479 --> 19:08.846
It was a very important part
of the defense

19:08.848 --> 19:11.082
of the United States
in the Pacific.

19:11.084 --> 19:13.217
WILDMAN:
The other is Johnston Island,

19:13.219 --> 19:15.419
a military outpost
and naval air station

19:15.421 --> 19:19.056
720 miles southwest of Hawaii.

19:19.058 --> 19:22.593
Both are vital to the American
military, but the U.S. Navy,

19:22.595 --> 19:25.129
depleted after the attack
on Pearl Harbor,

19:25.131 --> 19:29.867
only has enough ships
to defend one of them.

19:29.869 --> 19:33.337
WEADON: If you guess wrong,
you might just end up

19:33.339 --> 19:36.874
having Hawaii wide open
for invasion,

19:36.876 --> 19:39.877
so you're talking about
a critical situation.

19:39.879 --> 19:43.147
WILDMAN: Rochefort needs to find
a way to definitively figure out

19:43.149 --> 19:45.416
which island
the enemy will attack.

19:45.418 --> 19:48.152
Rochefort cannot allow
another Pearl Harbor.

19:48.154 --> 19:51.856
He must come up with a plan
to thwart the Japanese.

19:51.858 --> 19:56.594
♪♪

19:58.198 --> 19:59.664
♪♪

19:59.666 --> 20:03.668
It's May 1942,
Pearl Harbor, Hawaii.

20:03.670 --> 20:05.437
After months of work,

20:05.439 --> 20:08.640
Navy officer and cryptologist
Joseph Rochefort

20:08.642 --> 20:11.376
believes he's cracked
the Japanese Naval codes.

20:11.378 --> 20:13.278
He's certain
their next target will be

20:13.280 --> 20:15.447
a military base near Hawaii,

20:15.449 --> 20:18.383
possibly Johnston Island
or Midway.

20:18.385 --> 20:21.686
But which is it?

20:21.688 --> 20:24.089
To figure out for sure
which island

20:24.091 --> 20:26.024
is the next Japanese target,

20:26.026 --> 20:28.360
Rochefort comes up with
a clever trap.

20:28.362 --> 20:31.696
Knowing that the enemy is
monitoring U.S. Naval airwaves,

20:31.698 --> 20:33.398
he orders the base at Midway

20:33.400 --> 20:37.035
to send out a fake
emergency message to Hawaii.

20:37.037 --> 20:40.372
The decoy message states
that the desalinization plant

20:40.374 --> 20:43.608
that provides fresh water to
the island is broken.

20:45.646 --> 20:47.412
He is baiting the Japanese.

20:47.414 --> 20:50.982
He's setting up a convenient
cryptologic trap.

20:50.984 --> 20:53.518
WILDMAN: As anticipated,
Rochefort's team

20:53.520 --> 20:56.421
then intercepts a message
from the Japanese.

20:56.423 --> 20:59.424
In it, they alert their troops
that their next target

20:59.426 --> 21:00.825
is lacking fresh water,

21:00.827 --> 21:03.261
and they should bring
extra supplies.

21:03.263 --> 21:05.597
The trick has succeeded.

21:05.599 --> 21:07.666
The target is Midway.

21:07.668 --> 21:09.834
WEADON:
It worked exceedingly well.

21:09.836 --> 21:13.171
It made it very clear
that it was Midway.

21:13.173 --> 21:18.076
Rochefort probably felt
a huge amount of satisfaction.

21:18.078 --> 21:19.578
WILDMAN: Rochefort's superiors

21:19.580 --> 21:22.614
order the U.S. Navy into
position, northeast of Midway,

21:22.616 --> 21:25.283
in anticipation
of a Japanese attack.

21:27.688 --> 21:31.222
And 2 weeks later,
on June 4, 1942,

21:31.224 --> 21:34.192
Japanese ships appear
on the horizon.

21:34.194 --> 21:38.430
But the Americans
are ready and waiting.

21:38.432 --> 21:41.533
WEADON: For once, we're able
to turn the tables on them.

21:41.535 --> 21:43.902
The Japanese had won
so many battles

21:43.904 --> 21:47.205
that they just didn't think
they could ever be defeated.

21:47.207 --> 21:49.140
WILDMAN:
Because of Rochefort's effort,

21:49.142 --> 21:52.477
the United States triumphs
at the Battle of Midway.

21:52.479 --> 21:55.647
It marks a major turning point
in World War II.

21:55.649 --> 21:59.217
WEADON: The ability to prevail
at Midway had a critical effect

21:59.219 --> 22:01.386
on being able to win
the Pacific War

22:01.388 --> 22:02.654
as quickly as we did.

22:02.656 --> 22:04.689
It was sweet revenge.

22:06.259 --> 22:08.493
WILDMAN: For his contribution
to the war effort,

22:08.495 --> 22:12.430
Joseph Rochefort is awarded
the Distinguished Service Medal,

22:12.432 --> 22:14.699
and today,
this code-breaking machine,

22:14.701 --> 22:17.135
just like the one used
by Joseph Rochefort,

22:17.137 --> 22:20.105
is on display at
the National Cryptologic Museum

22:20.107 --> 22:22.474
in Annapolis Junction, Maryland.

22:22.476 --> 22:25.710
It serves as a reminder of how
one man's genius

22:25.712 --> 22:27.846
beat the enemy
at their own game.

22:27.848 --> 22:32.050
♪♪

22:32.052 --> 22:34.886
Malmesbury is
the oldest borough in England,

22:34.888 --> 22:37.922
dating back to the year 880.

22:37.924 --> 22:40.959
Today, the area is known
for its 12th-century abbey,

22:40.961 --> 22:42.894
which serves as
the unlikely site

22:42.896 --> 22:45.797
of an annual
skateboarding event.

22:45.799 --> 22:48.166
Every year, hoards
of young boarders

22:48.168 --> 22:51.136
come to test out the half-pipes,
rails, and jumps

22:51.138 --> 22:54.172
that are set up
inside the ancient church.

22:54.174 --> 22:57.676
And only a few blocks away
is an institution that documents

22:57.678 --> 23:00.645
the long and varied history
of the region --

23:00.647 --> 23:02.547
the Athelstan Museum.

23:02.549 --> 23:05.350
♪♪

23:05.352 --> 23:09.888
On display is a grinding stone
from the Iron Age,

23:09.890 --> 23:12.891
books written by the English
philosopher Thomas Hobbes,

23:12.893 --> 23:15.960
who was born here in 1588,

23:15.962 --> 23:17.896
and lace that was made
in Malmesbury

23:17.898 --> 23:19.831
at the turn of the 20th century.

23:22.335 --> 23:25.336
But among these artifacts
that have stood the test of time

23:25.338 --> 23:28.940
is a selection of souvenirs
from the modern day.

23:28.942 --> 23:30.675
ALCOCK:
The items are approximately

23:30.677 --> 23:33.611
4 inches tall by 6 inches wide.

23:33.613 --> 23:35.814
Black font can be seen
on the paper.

23:35.816 --> 23:37.348
They have white borders

23:37.350 --> 23:39.451
surrounding
colorful illustrations.

23:42.889 --> 23:46.624
WILDMAN: These postcards recall
a pair of unlikely heroes

23:46.626 --> 23:48.827
and their daring bid
for freedom.

23:48.829 --> 23:51.996
ALCOCK: These objects represent
two unique runaways

23:51.998 --> 23:53.998
whose escape excited a nation.

23:54.000 --> 23:58.503
♪♪

23:58.505 --> 24:01.840
WILDMAN:
January 1998, England.

24:01.842 --> 24:05.844
A massive hunt is underway
for two desperate fugitives,

24:05.846 --> 24:09.280
but the runaways in question
are not people.

24:09.282 --> 24:12.217
They're pigs.

24:12.219 --> 24:14.619
In fact, they're two
little porkers,

24:14.621 --> 24:17.822
aptly named Butch and Sundance.

24:17.824 --> 24:20.425
Several days earlier,
the 6-month-old piglets

24:20.427 --> 24:23.261
had leapt off a truck
bound for the slaughterhouse.

24:23.263 --> 24:26.097
Then the daring duo
dashed across a highway,

24:26.099 --> 24:27.432
through a river,

24:27.434 --> 24:30.735
and took refuge in a large
and impenetrable thicket.

24:30.737 --> 24:32.570
For the four-legged fugitives,

24:32.572 --> 24:35.073
the stakes could hardly
be higher.

24:35.075 --> 24:38.076
Their owners has made it clear
that when the pigs are caught,

24:38.078 --> 24:41.045
they will be sent
straight to the abattoir.

24:41.047 --> 24:43.214
It seems that
Butch and Sundance's days

24:43.216 --> 24:44.582
are truly numbered,

24:44.584 --> 24:47.719
but the oinking outlaws have
an unlikely ally.

24:49.756 --> 24:52.791
ALCOCK:
There's a great affection
in Britain for animals,

24:52.793 --> 24:54.993
and the plucky escape
from an abattoir

24:54.995 --> 24:57.629
really captured
people's imaginations,

24:57.631 --> 25:01.065
and so all those
perfect combinations

25:01.067 --> 25:04.402
came together to form
a real media frenzy.

25:04.404 --> 25:05.904
WILDMAN: The nation is gripped

25:05.906 --> 25:07.739
by the tale
of the slippery swine,

25:07.741 --> 25:11.342
and the race is on to save them
from their grisly fate.

25:11.344 --> 25:13.011
♪♪

25:13.013 --> 25:15.647
ALCOCK: All of the journalists
that descended upon the area

25:15.649 --> 25:16.881
are searching the thickets.

25:16.883 --> 25:18.316
They're wandering through
the woods.

25:18.318 --> 25:21.419
They're hoping to be the ones
to catch the pigs.

25:21.421 --> 25:23.454
WILDMAN: Among the throng
is a young reporter

25:23.456 --> 25:25.890
from the London-based
"Daily Mail."

25:25.892 --> 25:28.393
Her name is Barbara Davies.

25:28.395 --> 25:30.061
ALCOCK: Barbara Davies was

25:30.063 --> 25:33.031
a relatively new journalist
at the "Daily Mail."

25:33.033 --> 25:34.499
She was young.

25:34.501 --> 25:38.703
She was driven, and Barbara
was determined to get a scoop.

25:38.705 --> 25:40.905
WILDMAN:
But the competition is fierce.

25:40.907 --> 25:42.974
♪♪

25:42.976 --> 25:45.443
The finest investigative
journalists in the land

25:45.445 --> 25:46.978
are going head-to-head

25:46.980 --> 25:49.981
to be the first
to find the rogue hogs' hideout.

25:49.983 --> 25:52.817
Each is desperate to put
their name on the front page

25:52.819 --> 25:55.086
with the nation's biggest story.

25:55.088 --> 25:58.122
So how is Davies going to
outrun the reporters

25:58.124 --> 26:00.792
and track down
the tricky trotters?

26:00.794 --> 26:03.528
♪♪

26:05.164 --> 26:06.564
♪♪

26:06.566 --> 26:09.867
It's January 1998 in England.

26:09.869 --> 26:13.604
The nation is in the thralls
of an incredible news story.

26:13.606 --> 26:14.905
Butch and Sundance,

26:14.907 --> 26:17.808
two little piggies
bound for the slaughterhouse,

26:17.810 --> 26:20.878
have broken their bonds
and are now out on the lam.

26:20.880 --> 26:24.915
Their owner has vowed to catch
them and turn them into sausage,

26:24.917 --> 26:28.586
but now a young journalist named
Barbara Davies is on the case.

26:28.588 --> 26:32.156
So can she save
the curly tailed twosome?

26:33.659 --> 26:36.393
Key to her strategy
is an obscure detail

26:36.395 --> 26:38.696
about the daily life of pigs.

26:38.698 --> 26:41.565
They are nocturnal.

26:41.567 --> 26:43.434
Together, with a team of locals,

26:43.436 --> 26:46.370
including the owners of
a nearby animal sanctuary,

26:46.372 --> 26:48.839
Davies plunges into the night

26:48.841 --> 26:51.408
with sacks of nuts
to lure the hungry hogs

26:51.410 --> 26:53.110
and ropes to tie them.

26:53.112 --> 26:56.647
The band of pig hunters creeps
through the dark woods.

26:56.649 --> 26:59.583
ALCOCK: It became a night
of very near misses,

26:59.585 --> 27:01.752
glimpses of the two
through the undergrowth,

27:01.754 --> 27:03.554
the sounds of them
in the distance,

27:03.556 --> 27:06.524
but no physical contact
with the pigs.

27:06.526 --> 27:09.860
♪♪

27:09.862 --> 27:12.663
WILDMAN: Finally, just as dawn
is beginning to break,

27:12.665 --> 27:14.498
they see movement.

27:14.500 --> 27:17.501
♪♪

27:17.503 --> 27:21.205
Suddenly, Butch was
right in front of them.

27:21.207 --> 27:23.908
WILDMAN: Davies and her team
pounce on the runaway.

27:23.910 --> 27:26.477
ALCOCK: Davies must have
felt ecstatic.

27:26.479 --> 27:28.445
She must have had her heart
in her mouth.

27:28.447 --> 27:30.047
She's got her scoop.

27:30.049 --> 27:32.850
♪♪

27:32.852 --> 27:34.184
WILDMAN: A short time later,

27:34.186 --> 27:36.053
seeing his partner has
been captured,

27:36.055 --> 27:37.922
Sundance gives up.

27:37.924 --> 27:39.456
Everyone knew that her brother

27:39.458 --> 27:41.191
wouldn't have strayed far
without her,

27:41.193 --> 27:43.127
and so the second pig, Sundance,

27:43.129 --> 27:46.297
was finally located
and captured.

27:46.299 --> 27:48.432
WILDMAN:
The hunt for the pigs is over,

27:48.434 --> 27:52.002
and Davies gets
her world "oinksclusive,"

27:52.004 --> 27:54.939
but Butch and Sundance
aren't out of the woods yet.

27:57.176 --> 28:01.412
Their owner is still hell-bent
on turning them into sausages.

28:01.414 --> 28:04.481
Absolutely no one,
in the whole of Britain,

28:04.483 --> 28:05.983
around the entire world,

28:05.985 --> 28:08.319
wanted to see these pigs
go to the abattoir.

28:08.321 --> 28:12.022
Everybody wants a happy ending.

28:12.024 --> 28:14.291
WILDMAN: So Davies' editor
at the "Daily Mail"

28:14.293 --> 28:17.695
makes the pigs' owner
an offer he can't refuse.

28:17.697 --> 28:21.765
Much to everybody's relief,
in England and around the world,

28:21.767 --> 28:23.701
the owner of the pigs announces

28:23.703 --> 28:27.571
that he's going to sell
the pigs to the "Daily Mail."

28:27.573 --> 28:29.573
WILDMAN: The newspaper sends
Butch and Sundance

28:29.575 --> 28:32.509
to live high on the hog
in a luxury pen

28:32.511 --> 28:35.179
on a 100-acre sanctuary.

28:35.181 --> 28:38.248
ALCOCK: This was absolutely
the best outcome imaginable.

28:38.250 --> 28:41.185
They were gonna live out
their days as long as they could

28:41.187 --> 28:43.320
in happiness
in a beautiful location.

28:43.322 --> 28:47.524
♪♪

28:47.526 --> 28:49.627
WILDMAN:
Today, these souvenir postcards

28:49.629 --> 28:52.029
depicting the pigs' days
on the lam

28:52.031 --> 28:54.531
are on display
at the Athelstan Museum

28:54.533 --> 28:56.000
in Malmesbury, England.

28:56.002 --> 28:58.502
They recall two of Britain's
most prized

28:58.504 --> 29:00.871
and audacious porkers.

29:02.341 --> 29:04.541
The elegant
19th-century mansions

29:04.543 --> 29:07.211
that line Washington D.C.'s
Embassy Row

29:07.213 --> 29:09.713
are home to
the official diplomatic outposts

29:09.715 --> 29:12.716
of more than 170 nations.

29:12.718 --> 29:16.587
Every year in May, many open
their doors to the public.

29:16.589 --> 29:18.922
But a few blocks away
is an historic building

29:18.924 --> 29:21.091
with a very different purpose.

29:21.093 --> 29:24.361
This is the African American
Civil War Museum.

29:24.363 --> 29:27.431
♪♪

29:27.433 --> 29:30.434
The institution documents
the stories and experiences

29:30.436 --> 29:32.670
of African-Americans
during and after

29:32.672 --> 29:34.471
this historic conflict.

29:34.473 --> 29:37.708
On display is
a water canteen once carried

29:37.710 --> 29:41.412
by a member of
the 10th U.S. Colored Infantry,

29:41.414 --> 29:45.482
a Union belt buckle that has
been engraved with an eagle,

29:45.484 --> 29:47.651
and a fighting manual
that gives guidance

29:47.653 --> 29:49.653
on tactics and maneuvers.

29:51.957 --> 29:55.726
But the item here with a truly
extraordinary tale to tell

29:55.728 --> 29:58.262
is a soldier's most critical
piece of equipment.

29:58.264 --> 30:00.931
SMITH:
It's over 150 years old.

30:00.933 --> 30:03.333
It weighs about 10 pounds.

30:03.335 --> 30:05.369
It has the eagle on the side,

30:05.371 --> 30:07.471
and it's still
in good working condition.

30:07.473 --> 30:10.541
♪♪

30:10.543 --> 30:13.744
WILDMAN: This antique musket is
linked to a brave trooper

30:13.746 --> 30:15.779
who truly stood out
from the crowd.

30:15.781 --> 30:19.083
This artifact recalls
a story of how a disguise

30:19.085 --> 30:21.518
led to an historic first.

30:21.520 --> 30:25.422
♪♪

30:25.424 --> 30:28.025
WILDMAN:
It's the spring of 1865.

30:28.027 --> 30:30.094
After 4 long years of fighting,

30:30.096 --> 30:32.763
the Confederacy finally
surrenders to the Union,

30:32.765 --> 30:35.799
and the Civil War
comes to a close.

30:35.801 --> 30:39.036
In the aftermath, civilians
and soldiers alike are left

30:39.038 --> 30:42.873
to rebuild their lives
in the shadow of the conflict.

30:42.875 --> 30:44.808
One woman struggling
to find her way

30:44.810 --> 30:46.643
in this new and uncertain world

30:46.645 --> 30:49.880
is a cook for the Union Army
named Cathay Williams.

30:49.882 --> 30:51.849
SMITH:
Her whole horizon has changed.

30:51.851 --> 30:53.517
She has to find a way
to make a living.

30:53.519 --> 30:56.220
She wants to live
and be independent.

30:58.591 --> 31:02.526
WILDMAN: But few opportunities
exist for African-Americans.

31:02.528 --> 31:03.861
SMITH: Cathay Williams,

31:03.863 --> 31:05.496
like 200,000
other African-Americans

31:05.498 --> 31:06.630
who had been in the Army

31:06.632 --> 31:09.466
and all of these 3.9 million
enslaved persons

31:09.468 --> 31:10.868
who were now free,

31:10.870 --> 31:13.370
they had to figure out how
to make a life for themselves.

31:13.372 --> 31:16.106
♪♪

31:16.108 --> 31:18.342
WILDMAN: So when she learns that
the government

31:18.344 --> 31:21.278
is hiring soldiers to patrol
the Western territories,

31:21.280 --> 31:22.946
she sees an opportunity.

31:22.948 --> 31:25.849
Part of this was adventure.
She was adventurous.

31:25.851 --> 31:29.153
She wanted to taste some
of this life of being out West

31:29.155 --> 31:31.155
and riding into the sunset.

31:31.157 --> 31:33.524
♪♪

31:33.526 --> 31:35.159
WILDMAN:
But there's a problem.

31:35.161 --> 31:38.128
Women aren't allowed to serve
as soldiers.

31:38.130 --> 31:40.264
Williams considers
her alternatives

31:40.266 --> 31:42.866
and chooses
a bold course of action.

31:42.868 --> 31:45.569
Taking advantage
of her unusual height,

31:45.571 --> 31:49.473
she will disguise herself
as a man.

31:49.475 --> 31:52.376
She was 5-feet-9,
so she was a little bit taller

31:52.378 --> 31:53.844
than the ordinary woman.

31:53.846 --> 31:56.313
WILDMAN: Williams cuts her hair
to a short crop

31:56.315 --> 31:59.616
and dons men's clothing.

31:59.618 --> 32:02.419
And on November 15, 1866,

32:02.421 --> 32:06.456
Williams walks into the Army
offices disguised as a man.

32:06.458 --> 32:09.059
The recruiter doesn't
suspect a thing.

32:09.061 --> 32:10.727
SMITH: They didn't care
that much about

32:10.729 --> 32:12.563
what the physical appearance
was.

32:12.565 --> 32:17.835
There was a lot of emphasis
on your physical capability.

32:17.837 --> 32:20.037
WILDMAN: Williams signs her name
on the papers

32:20.039 --> 32:23.674
to join the United States Army
as "William Cathay."

32:23.676 --> 32:25.075
It's a big moment.

32:25.077 --> 32:28.445
Impersonating a male soldier
is a serious crime.

32:28.447 --> 32:31.315
If she's caught,
she could face imprisonment.

32:31.317 --> 32:33.951
She was taking a risk.
There's no question about it.

32:33.953 --> 32:37.621
WILDMAN: So how long will it be
before Williams is found out?

32:37.623 --> 32:40.991
♪♪

32:43.195 --> 32:44.761
♪♪

32:44.763 --> 32:47.431
It's 1886 in Missouri.

32:47.433 --> 32:50.367
22-year-old former slave
Cathay Williams

32:50.369 --> 32:52.436
has made a momentous decision.

32:52.438 --> 32:56.640
She's disguised herself as a man
and enlisted in the U.S. Army.

32:56.642 --> 32:58.876
So will her ruse work?

33:00.246 --> 33:03.480
Williams is placed
in the 38th U.S. Infantry,

33:03.482 --> 33:06.383
a regiment known as
the Buffalo Soldiers.

33:06.385 --> 33:08.819
The Indians gave them
the name Buffalo Soldiers

33:08.821 --> 33:11.522
out of respect and admiration
for how hard they fought.

33:11.524 --> 33:13.223
WILDMAN: For two years,

33:13.225 --> 33:16.426
Williams travels the breadth
of the Western frontier.

33:16.428 --> 33:18.629
She masterfully
keeps up the charade,

33:18.631 --> 33:22.165
knowing she can shoot,
march, and follow orders

33:22.167 --> 33:26.169
as well as any of
the other soldiers,

33:26.171 --> 33:29.106
but while stationed at
Fort Bayard in New Mexico,

33:29.108 --> 33:32.976
she begins experiencing
sharp, stabbing pains.

33:32.978 --> 33:35.412
Eventually, the pains
become so severe

33:35.414 --> 33:37.714
that she knows
she must see a doctor.

33:37.716 --> 33:41.184
SMITH: Williams was able to
keep up her facade for a while,

33:41.186 --> 33:42.452
but she couldn't hide it
forever.

33:42.454 --> 33:44.421
♪♪

33:44.423 --> 33:47.090
WILDMAN: Tentatively,
Williams explains her symptoms

33:47.092 --> 33:48.525
to an Army doctor.

33:48.527 --> 33:50.027
He treats her pain,

33:50.029 --> 33:52.529
and in doing so,
learns her secret.

33:52.531 --> 33:55.666
They were shocked when they
discovered that she was a woman.

33:55.668 --> 33:57.100
WILDMAN:
The doctor has no choice

33:57.102 --> 34:01.572
but to report his findings
to the authorities.

34:01.574 --> 34:05.709
To her relief, her superiors
decide not to press charges,

34:05.711 --> 34:09.279
but to release her from service
with a certificate of disability

34:09.281 --> 34:13.216
stating that William Cathay
is simply unfit for duty.

34:13.218 --> 34:15.586
They admired her for her body
of work that she had done

34:15.588 --> 34:16.887
while she was in there,

34:16.889 --> 34:20.857
that she was able to keep up
and do what they did.

34:20.859 --> 34:24.628
Today, Williams is recognized as
the first African-American woman

34:24.630 --> 34:26.697
to enlist in the Army

34:26.699 --> 34:31.001
and the only one documented to
serve while posing as a man.

34:31.003 --> 34:33.036
Cathay Williams was one of
those people in history

34:33.038 --> 34:36.106
who has proven that women
can do anything that men can do.

34:38.711 --> 34:41.411
This musket,
like the one Williams used

34:41.413 --> 34:43.413
during her time
as a Buffalo Soldier,

34:43.415 --> 34:44.748
remains on display

34:44.750 --> 34:47.250
at the African American
Civil War Museum

34:47.252 --> 34:48.785
in Washington, D.C.

34:48.787 --> 34:50.420
It recalls a determined woman

34:50.422 --> 34:53.991
whose desire to serve her
country couldn't be disguised.

34:53.993 --> 34:56.627
♪♪

34:56.629 --> 34:58.428
Sioux Falls, South Dakota,

34:58.430 --> 35:00.564
was named not only
for the Sioux Indians

35:00.566 --> 35:02.532
that once inhabited the land,

35:02.534 --> 35:05.535
but also
its stunning waterfalls.

35:05.537 --> 35:07.838
As the city's
number one attraction,

35:07.840 --> 35:10.941
Falls Park features 123 acres,

35:10.943 --> 35:13.610
through which more than
7,000 gallons of water

35:13.612 --> 35:15.712
flow every second.

35:15.714 --> 35:18.115
Just an hour away,
in the city of Yankton,

35:18.117 --> 35:19.650
is an institution dedicated

35:19.652 --> 35:22.386
to a very different kind
of spectacle --

35:22.388 --> 35:26.056
the National Field Archery
Association and Museum.

35:26.058 --> 35:28.959
♪♪

35:28.961 --> 35:31.928
Celebrating the history
of archery and bowmanship,

35:31.930 --> 35:34.698
the collection includes
hand-painted arrows

35:34.700 --> 35:38.335
with vanes made
from turkey feathers,

35:38.337 --> 35:40.671
an array of
archery-themed stamps

35:40.673 --> 35:42.372
from around the world,

35:42.374 --> 35:43.707
and a gold medal

35:43.709 --> 35:47.911
won at a National Field Archery
Indoor Championship.

35:47.913 --> 35:51.448
But one item here hearkens back
to a unique contest

35:51.450 --> 35:54.017
that has the unlikeliest
of origins.

35:54.019 --> 35:57.320
The artifact is
62 1/2 inches long.

35:57.322 --> 36:01.258
It has two ends that both curve
in the same direction.

36:01.260 --> 36:04.494
It has a bamboo core
with fiberglass over it.

36:04.496 --> 36:07.931
♪♪

36:07.933 --> 36:11.168
WILDMAN: This bow is linked to
a groundbreaking doctor

36:11.170 --> 36:13.804
who changed the world of sport
forever.

36:13.806 --> 36:16.540
MASTRACCO: This is a story
of how a new medical technique

36:16.542 --> 36:18.575
spawned a global sporting event.

36:18.577 --> 36:25.482
♪♪

36:25.484 --> 36:29.286
WILDMAN: It's February 1944,
Great Britain.

36:29.288 --> 36:33.223
Dr. Ludwig Guttmann is
a 45-year-old German doctor

36:33.225 --> 36:36.093
who has fled the Nazis
and taken refuge in England.

36:36.095 --> 36:38.628
Dr. Guttmann was a neurologist

36:38.630 --> 36:43.333
who specialized
in spinal chord injuries.

36:43.335 --> 36:45.469
WILDMAN: Now he is working
in one of the most challenging

36:45.471 --> 36:47.604
medical environments
in the country,

36:47.606 --> 36:51.341
Stoke Mandeville Hospital's
Ward X.

36:51.343 --> 36:54.111
It has beds for up
to 26 patients,

36:54.113 --> 36:55.912
many of them British airmen

36:55.914 --> 36:58.849
and all with
severe spinal injuries.

36:58.851 --> 37:01.985
Barely able to move, many of
the patients also suffer

37:01.987 --> 37:04.921
from bedsores
and respiratory infections.

37:04.923 --> 37:07.958
Few, if any,
are expected to improve.

37:07.960 --> 37:10.560
There really was no therapy
for paralyzed patients.

37:10.562 --> 37:11.828
They were stuck in casts

37:11.830 --> 37:14.464
and they were left
in their hospital beds.

37:16.902 --> 37:19.436
WILDMAN: But Dr. Guttmann is
determined to find a way

37:19.438 --> 37:21.471
to treat these desperate cases

37:21.473 --> 37:24.007
and offer them hope
for their future.

37:24.009 --> 37:25.475
MASTRACCO:
He wanted to change the way

37:25.477 --> 37:27.110
that paralysis was treated,

37:27.112 --> 37:30.680
to show that they can
still live normal lives.

37:30.682 --> 37:32.849
♪♪

37:32.851 --> 37:34.618
WILDMAN:
So the German medicine man

37:34.620 --> 37:38.221
starts to introduce a series
of innovations in the ward.

37:38.223 --> 37:40.590
First, he makes sure
the patients are moved

37:40.592 --> 37:41.892
on a regular basis.

37:41.894 --> 37:46.096
He would have his nurses
flip them once every few hours

37:46.098 --> 37:48.465
so that the bedsores
wouldn't develop.

37:48.467 --> 37:51.168
WILDMAN: Then he encourages them
to sit up.

37:51.170 --> 37:54.538
MASTRACCO: That was very
painful, nauseating for them,

37:54.540 --> 37:56.540
but it was small steps needed.

37:56.542 --> 37:59.543
♪♪

37:59.545 --> 38:01.011
WILDMAN:
Slowly but surely,

38:01.013 --> 38:04.247
Dr. Guttmann eases his patients
out of their beds.

38:04.249 --> 38:05.882
A lot of them moved
into wheelchairs

38:05.884 --> 38:08.919
and were doing smaller
physical activities.

38:08.921 --> 38:10.253
WILDMAN:
But despite his efforts,

38:10.255 --> 38:12.322
Dr. Guttmann realizes
that improving

38:12.324 --> 38:15.725
his patients' physical
well-being isn't enough.

38:15.727 --> 38:18.662
He must also raise their morale.

38:18.664 --> 38:22.699
He wanted them to realize
there was more to live for.

38:22.701 --> 38:25.602
WILDMAN: What he does next
will echo down the ages

38:25.604 --> 38:27.337
and forever change the lives

38:27.339 --> 38:29.606
of paralyzed people
around the world.

38:29.608 --> 38:32.008
His ideas were about
to go global.

38:32.010 --> 38:38.582
♪♪

38:40.219 --> 38:41.719
♪♪

38:41.721 --> 38:44.455
It's 1944 in England.

38:44.457 --> 38:47.892
A pioneering doctor named
Ludwig Guttmann is determined

38:47.894 --> 38:51.128
to improve the way
paralyzed patients are treated.

38:51.130 --> 38:53.364
So far, he's helped them
progress physically,

38:53.366 --> 38:56.534
but he can't figure out
how to boost their morale.

38:56.536 --> 38:58.836
Little does he know, he's about
to come up with an idea

38:58.838 --> 39:03.741
that will do far more
than just lift their spirits.

39:03.743 --> 39:07.044
Dr. Guttmann has an idea --

39:07.046 --> 39:09.613
sports.

39:09.615 --> 39:11.949
MASTRACCO: To Dr. Guttmann,
sports were more than

39:11.951 --> 39:15.452
just a form of physical exercise
and a form of therapy.

39:15.454 --> 39:17.755
Exercise boosts your mood.

39:17.757 --> 39:20.591
It makes you a happier person.

39:20.593 --> 39:23.227
WILDMAN: The doctor incorporates
table tennis,

39:23.229 --> 39:25.629
wheelchair basketball,
and archery

39:25.631 --> 39:28.165
into his rehabilitation program.

39:28.167 --> 39:30.267
The results are immediate.

39:30.269 --> 39:32.036
MASTRACCO:
Dr. Guttmann saw that sports

39:32.038 --> 39:34.605
were doing wonders for
these patients.

39:34.607 --> 39:37.675
♪♪

39:37.677 --> 39:39.977
WILDMAN: Building on
this success and inspired by

39:39.979 --> 39:44.048
the postwar London Olympic Games
of July 1948,

39:44.050 --> 39:46.951
Dr. Guttmann organizes
a small competition

39:46.953 --> 39:48.819
for wheelchair athletes.

39:48.821 --> 39:52.356
16 men and women participate
in what comes to be known

39:52.358 --> 39:54.358
as the Stoke Mandeville Games.

39:54.360 --> 39:55.893
MASTRACCO:
The Stoke Mandeville Games

39:55.895 --> 39:58.362
was a group of mostly
wounded soldiers,

39:58.364 --> 40:01.165
and he decided
to have them compete

40:01.167 --> 40:02.800
in a few different activities.

40:02.802 --> 40:04.134
WILDMAN:
In the years that follow,

40:04.136 --> 40:06.604
the games take on
a life of their own.

40:06.606 --> 40:09.840
And it became something
so much bigger

40:09.842 --> 40:12.009
than he initially imagined.

40:12.011 --> 40:14.578
♪♪

40:14.580 --> 40:18.282
WILDMAN: On September 18, 1960,
in Rome, Italy,

40:18.284 --> 40:20.718
in conjunction
with the Olympic Games,

40:20.720 --> 40:23.253
Dr. Guttmann launches
a brand-new event

40:23.255 --> 40:25.623
for disabled athletes
worldwide --

40:25.625 --> 40:26.957
the Paralympics.

40:26.959 --> 40:29.293
This was the first time
that we saw

40:29.295 --> 40:33.063
disabled athletes compete
on a world scale.

40:33.065 --> 40:36.367
WILDMAN: 400 wheelchair athletes
from 23 countries

40:36.369 --> 40:39.169
compete in sports such as
fencing, swimming,

40:39.171 --> 40:40.871
basketball and archery.

40:43.109 --> 40:46.810
One of Guttmann's own patients,
a woman named Margaret Maughan,

40:46.812 --> 40:49.146
even wins a gold medal
in archery,

40:49.148 --> 40:51.982
Britain's first gold
of the games.

40:51.984 --> 40:53.350
MASTRACCO: To Dr. Guttmann,
this had to be

40:53.352 --> 40:55.686
an immensely proud moment
in his life,

40:55.688 --> 40:59.790
because not only was he seeing
his dream of the games

40:59.792 --> 41:02.026
reaching athletes
around the globe,

41:02.028 --> 41:06.597
a patient that he personally
treated won a gold medal.

41:08.100 --> 41:10.601
WILDMAN: Since that time,
every 2 years,

41:10.603 --> 41:14.405
thousands of athletes
representing some 159 nations

41:14.407 --> 41:17.574
take part in the Winter
or Summer Paralympics,

41:17.576 --> 41:20.778
all due to the efforts of
Dr. Ludwig Guttmann.

41:20.780 --> 41:24.715
Dr. Guttmann became known as
the father of the Paralympics.

41:24.717 --> 41:28.185
♪♪

41:28.187 --> 41:30.387
WILDMAN: Today, this 1960s bow,

41:30.389 --> 41:32.890
just like the ones used
at the first Paralympics,

41:32.892 --> 41:34.291
is on display

41:34.293 --> 41:36.860
at the National Field Archery
Association and Museum

41:36.862 --> 41:38.929
in Yankton, South Dakota.

41:38.931 --> 41:41.632
It serves as a reminder of
a determined doctor

41:41.634 --> 41:43.734
who inspired
his afflicted patients

41:43.736 --> 41:46.303
toward athletic prowess.

41:46.305 --> 41:47.638
♪♪

41:47.640 --> 41:50.474
From a life and death
experiment

41:50.476 --> 41:52.643
to an epic escape,

41:52.645 --> 41:56.380
a daring disguise
to a brilliant code breaker,

41:56.382 --> 41:57.715
I'm Don Wildman,

41:57.717 --> 42:00.784
and these are
the mysteries at the museum.
